subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: On the accompanying map of part of the British Isles:

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Show and name four of the main coalfields of Britain.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Delimit two areas where the population density is very high.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Mark Edinburgh and Leeds, and show the Waverley-Midland Route.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Mark a limestone ridge which crosses England.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Mark two passenger steamship routes between Ireland and Great Britain.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: On the accompanying map of the lands surrounding the Indian Ocean:

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Write DRY, WINTER, SUMMER, ALL, TWO over appropriate areas.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Write OIL over two major oilfields.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Mark and name four entrepots.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Name Tasmania, Sumatra, Madagascar, and Mozambique, stating the Empire of which each forms a part.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Examine the contour map on page 4 of the map sheet:

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Write a broad general description of the build of the area shown.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Suggest reasons why a town has developed at S.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Comment on the position of the road SPQBU.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: If the map measures 5½ inches by 7, what area of territory is shown?

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Distinguish between transhumance and nomadism. Describe, with reference to a specific example in each case, how geographical conditions lead to the movements of the people.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: What are the conditions necessary for the cultivation and harvesting of cotton or tea? Give a broad account of the world distribution of the crop selected.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Explain with the help of diagrams:

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Why it is warmer at the Equator than at high latitudes.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Why the interval between sunrise and sunset varies with the seasons but not at the Equator.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Describe, with reference to a specific example in each case, the main characteristics of the build, drainage, and soil of a dissected plateau and an alluvial plain. Indicate how the physical characteristics influence human affairs.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Write a short essay showing how a serious deficiency in British coal production tends to bring about restrictions in our food supply, difficulties for our manufacturing industries, and a reduced standard of living.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Describe broadly the characteristics of the climate of your home area. Write notes showing how three of the following differ in climate from your home area: Cork, Dublin, Lowestoft, Braemar, Lerwick, Southampton.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Account for the distribution of people in one of the following areas: The Scottish Lowlands; England north of the Mersey-Humber; Wales; Ireland (Eire and Northern Ireland).

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: “Although geographically different, Norway and Denmark are much akin.” Expand and discuss this statement.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Write notes on the position and importance of three of the following: Basle; Coblenz; Essen; Hamburg; Istanbul; Madrid; Marseilles; Milan; Vienna.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Contrast the climate of two of the following areas, and mention the main agricultural products: The Plain of Lombardy; The Paris Basin; The Basin of the Vistula; S.W. Spain.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Suppose that you had recently spent a whole year on a farm in one of the following areas: The Lake Peninsula of Canada; Southern Manitoba; a valley of western Nova Scotia; the Australian Riverina; the eastern coastal plain of North Island, New Zealand; the south-western part of Cape Province, South Africa. Write a geographical essay describing your impressions.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: Draw a sketch-map of N. America showing the main physical regions. Give a general description of the build of one of these regions and write a brief note on the rest.

subject: GEOGRAPHY
text: “Africa remained for long the Dark Continent, so great were the obstacles which impeded exploration of the interior.” Mention the kinds of obstacles and illustrate by examples.
